==English==

===Etymology===
{{OE.}} ''[[afere]], [[affere]]'', {{OF.}} ''[[afaire]]'', {{F.}} ''[[affaire]]'', from a ''[[faire]]'' to do; Latin ''[[ad-]] + [[facere]]'' to do.  See [[Fact]], and confer [[Ado]].

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /əˈfɛɹ/

===Noun===
'''affair'''  (''plural:'' '''[[affairs]]''')
# That which is done or is to be done; matter; concern; as, a difficult affair to manage; business of any kind, commercial, professional, or public; &mdash; often in the  plural. 
# Any proceeding or action which it is wished to refer to or characterize vaguely; as, an affair of honor, i. e., a duel; an affair of love, i. e., an intrigue.
# ''(Military):'' An action or engagement not of sufficient magnitude to be called a battle.
# A material object (vaguely designated).
# An adulterous relationship. (from ''affaire de coeur''.)

